Fixture Paper: Evaluation of Persistent Memory in Coding Agents
DOI: 10.5555/hermes.fixture.2026.001

Abstract
We evaluate persistent memory systems for coding agents. The study compares raw evidence
retention, curated wiki synthesis, and ephemeral scratchpads across long-running repository tasks.

1. Introduction
Persistent agent memory can reduce repeated discovery and improve handoff quality when provenance is
preserved.

2. Methods
We reviewed source snapshots, page histories, and search projections under deterministic fixtures.

3. Results
Linked Wiki Pages improved recall of project-specific terms such as getCwd and HERMES_HOME.

References
[1] Fixture Research Collective. Rebuildable projections for agent memory. 2026.
